{0 Building a complete site}

odoc gives you an API reference. wodoc turns the same sources into a {b complete
website}: a styled home page, prose chapters, the API of one or several packages,
a shared top menu, a generated left navigation, a version selector, an optional
blog, Markdown twins for AI tools, and a deployable versioned tree — all from one
declarative {{!page-"config"}[doc/wodoc]} config and a single [wodoc build].

This page is the end-to-end walkthrough. It assumes you have read
{{!page-"overview"}How it works} and points to {{!page-"config"}Configuration}
and {{!page-"commands"}Commands} for the exhaustive reference of every stanza and
flag. A {b copy-paste starter} (a menu, a stylesheet and a CI workflow) lives in
{{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/tree/master/examples/starter}[examples/starter]} —
clone it and adjust the names rather than starting from a blank page.

{1 Quickstart}

From an existing dune project with a public library (say package [demo], whose
top module is [Demo], with documented [.mli]), three steps give you a styled site.

{2 1. Add a documentation page}

odoc builds the [.mld] pages of a package declared with a [(documentation …)]
stanza:

{@text[
mkdir doc
cat > doc/dune <<'EOF'
(documentation (package demo))
EOF
cat > doc/index.mld <<'EOF'
{0 Demo}

Welcome to {b Demo}. See the {!Demo} API.
EOF
]}

{2 2. Write the wodoc config}

{@text[
cat > doc/wodoc <<'EOF'
(project demo)
(title "Demo")
(url-prefix /demo)
(packages demo)
(landing demo/index.html)
(nav
 (section "Manual" (link "Home" demo/index.html index))
 (api-section "API" (link "Demo" demo/Demo/index.html Demo)))
EOF
]}

{2 3. Build and preview}

{@text[
wodoc build --config doc/wodoc --out _site/dev --label dev
# the result is in _site/
]}

[wodoc build] runs [dune build @doc] itself and assembles every page. The result
is a complete, {b styled, self-contained} site — no menu file, no stylesheet to
host. (Customise later with [--menu] and [(css …)]; see {{!theming}Theming}.)

{2 Add a blog}

Write a dated post — the filename date is the publication date, [@author] the
author, the first heading the title, the first paragraph the excerpt:

{@text[
mkdir doc/blog
cat > doc/blog/2026-01-15-hello.mld <<'EOF'
{0 Hello, world}

@author Jane Doe

Our very first post, announcing the demo.
EOF
]}

Declare the blog in [doc/wodoc] and drop a "latest posts" marker on the landing
([{%html:<!--wodoc-blog-latest-->%}] is the form that survives odoc):

{@text[
# append to doc/wodoc:
(blog (dir blog) (out blog) (heading "Blog") (latest 5))
]}

{@text[
# add to doc/index.mld where the list should appear:
{1 Latest posts}
{%html:<!--wodoc-blog-latest-->%}
]}

Rebuild with the same [wodoc build] command: the post is built at [blog/], listed
in a generated left-nav section, and the marker expands into a styled list. See
{{!page-"blog"}Adding a blog} for the Atom feed and the navigation block.

{1 What "a complete website" means}

A wodoc site is made of these ingredients; each is covered below.

- a {b home / landing page} — your styled front page, not the bare API index;
- {b prose pages} — chapters, tutorials, guides (plain [.mld] files);
- the {b API} — the [.mli] of one package, or several packages side by side;
- a {b top menu} — the site-wide header (your brand, links), shared by every page;
- a {b left navigation} — generated from the config, with the current entry marked;
- a {b version selector} — [dev], released versions and [latest], from a manifest;
- a {b theme} — the stylesheet that makes all of the above look like a site;
- optionally a {b blog} and {b Markdown twins} for AI tools;
- a {b deployment} — a versioned tree published to (typically) GitHub Pages.

{1 The shape of a built site}

[wodoc build --out <dir> --label <v>] writes {e one version} of the site into
[<dir>]. Deployed, the tree looks like this (here [(url-prefix /myproj)], one package):

{@text[
/myproj/
  dev/                 <- a build (--label dev)
    index.html         <- redirect to the landing page
    myproj/            <- the package's pages (manual + API)
      index.html       <- the home page
      tutorial.html
      Myproj/index.html
    wodoc.css          <- the theme (built-in default, or your (css …))
    wodoc-highlight.js
    versions.json      <- the version manifest (drives the <select>)
  1.0.0/               <- a frozen release (wodoc release)
  latest -> 1.0.0      <- a symlink
]}

Everything a page references — the theme, the highlighter, internal links — is
version-relative, so the site is self-contained and a frozen version keeps working
forever. (Only the version [<select>] uses the absolute [(url-prefix)] to switch
versions.)

{1 [wodoc build]: what it generates, what you supply}

The turn-key {{!page-"commands"}[wodoc build]} runs [dune build @doc] and then
assembles every page. It {b generates almost everything} — including a default
theme and top bar — so a basic site needs no theming setup at all.

{t
  | Part | Who provides it |
  |------|-----------------|
  | the HTML page template (head, two-column body, scripts) | {b generated} |
  | the left navigation, "on this page", version [<select>] and its script | {b generated} (from the config) |
  | the page content (odoc HTML, with your [{%wodoc:…%}] markers rendered) | {b generated} |
  | Markdown twins, [llms.txt], the landing redirect, [versions.json] | {b generated} |
  | the highlighter ([highlight.pack.js] and [wodoc-highlight.js]) | {b shipped} by wodoc |
  | the {b top bar} | {b generated} default; override with [--menu] (a file or URL) |
  | the {b stylesheet / theme} | {b shipped} default [wodoc.css]; override with [(css …)] |
  | static assets (images, examples) | {b you} (via config; see below) |
}

So the minimal build is just:

{@text[
wodoc build --config doc/wodoc --out _site/dev --label dev
]}

That already produces a {b styled, self-contained site} — a built-in theme and a
top bar are shipped and linked by per-version relative paths, so it works at any
deploy path. The rest of this page is about the pieces you may want to customise:
the home page, the navigation, and — when you outgrow the built-in look — the
theme and the top bar.

{1 The home page}

The landing page is just one of your [.mld] pages, assembled like any other — so
you style it with the full {{!page-"directives"}directive set} ([{%wodoc:div%}],
[{%wodoc:@ class=…%}], [{%wodoc:img%}], the semantic block containers…) to make a
real front page rather than a wall of text.

Point the config's [(landing …)] stanza at it:

{@text[
(landing myproj/index.html)
]}

[wodoc build] then writes a tiny [index.html] at the version root that redirects
to that page, so [/myproj/dev/] lands on your home page. (A
{{!page-"config"}manual-only project} whose landing {e is} the root [index.html]
gets a real page there instead of a redirect.)

{1 General (prose) pages}

Any [.mld] file compiled by [dune build @doc] becomes a page: write chapters,
tutorials and guides as ordinary odoc pages and list them in the navigation (next
section). Keep them {b portable} — see {{!page-"authoring"}Authoring} for which
constructs survive on ocaml.org and which are wodoc-only chrome. Migrating an old
wikicréole manual? Run {{!page-"commands"}[wodoc convert]} once to bootstrap the
[.mld] files, then review them.

{1 The left navigation}

The left column is declared, not hand-written, in the config's [(nav …)] stanza:

{@text[
(nav
 (section "Manual"
  (link "Overview" myproj/index.html index)
  (link "Tutorial" myproj/tutorial.html tutorial)
  (group "Advanced"
   (link "Internals" myproj/internals.html internals)))
 (api-section "API"
  (link "API overview" myproj/Myproj/index.html Myproj)))
]}

Each [(link "Label" <path> <id>)] gives the visible label, a version-relative
path and the page's odoc [<id>] — wodoc marks the matching entry [current] on
each page automatically (longest-prefix match, so you never hand-maintain
"current" flags). [(group …)] nests a sub-heading; [(section …)] is a manual
block, [(api-section …)] an API block. A project whose versions have {e different}
manuals can pass a per-version navigation with [wodoc build --nav <file>] (same
syntax). The full grammar is in {{!page-"config"}Configuration}.

{1 API docs: one package or several}

For a single library, [(packages myproj)] assembles its [dune build @doc] output.
List several to document them side by side:

{@text[
(packages myproj myproj-lwt myproj-unix)
]}

A {b client/server} project (libraries that share module names, e.g. an Eliom
app) is built through [odoc_driver] instead of [dune build @doc]. Just declare a
[(client-server …)] block (it implies [(odoc-driver <project>)]); wodoc then gives
every page its side's API nav, a body colour and a client/server switch. See the
[(client-server …)] stanza in {{!page-"config"}Configuration}.

{1:theming Theming: customising the look}

[wodoc build] ships a built-in theme and a default top bar (the section above),
so you can skip this entirely and still get a styled site. Customise when you
outgrow the defaults.

{2 The top bar ([--menu])}

Pass [--menu <file|URL>] to replace the default bar with your own HTML {e fragment}
(a local file or an [http(s)] URL fetched with curl), injected at the top of every
page. It may contain holes wodoc fills: [{{subproject}}] (your title) and
[{{base}}] (the per-page relative path to the version root). A minimal menu:

{@text[
<header class="site-header">
  <a class="site-brand" href="/">My Project</a>
  {{subproject}}
  <nav class="site-nav"><a href="{{base}}/index.html">Docs</a></nav>
</header>
]}

{2 The stylesheet ([(css …)])}

By default wodoc links its built-in theme ([wodoc.css], shipped per-version). The
[(css …)] stanza replaces it; the template does {e not} link odoc's own [odoc.css],
so your stylesheets carry the whole look. Choose how they are served:

- [(css style.css …)] — {b relative} hrefs: wodoc copies each file (found next to
  the config) into every build and links it per-version, so the site stays
  {b self-contained} and works at any deploy path;
- [(css /css/style.css …)] or a full URL — {b absolute} hrefs, emitted verbatim,
  which you serve yourself (e.g. a shared site-wide stylesheet at the domain root).

A custom stylesheet must style both the chrome and the content:

- the chrome wodoc emits — [.wodoc-page], [.project-page]/[.twocols]/[.leftcol]/
  [.rightcol], the navigation ([.api-nav], [.api-section], [.ml2]/[.ml3]/…,
  [li.current]), [.docversion]/[.wodoc-version], [.page-toc], [.cs-switch] and the
  blog [.wodoc-blog-*] classes;
- the odoc {b content} — [.odoc-preamble]/[.odoc-content], headings, code blocks
  (highlight.js [.hljs-*] tokens), tables and declaration specs.

The {{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/tree/master/examples/starter/css}starter
stylesheet} covers all of these — copy it and recolour. (If you would rather
reuse odoc's stock theme for the content, note that [odoc.css] {e is} shipped next
to each version, so you can link or [@import] it from your [/css/ocsigen-odoc.css].)

Syntax highlighting: wodoc always ships [wodoc-highlight.js] in each build, but the
template only loads it locally when the config sets [(highlight <file>)] —
otherwise it loads the shared [/doc/wodoc-highlight.js]. Set
[(highlight wodoc-highlight.js)] (the starter does) so your site uses its own
local copy.

{1 Several projects that cross-link}

A site can host several {e independent} projects (each its own [wodoc build],
deployed into a shared tree) whose docs cross-reference each other. odoc points
such cross-references at ocaml.org; the [(hosted …)] stanza rewrites them into
relative links to the sibling project, given how that project is deployed:

{@text[
(hosted (myproj myproj multilib Myproj)
        (otherproj otherproj root "")
        (bigproj bigproj subdir ""))
]}

The layout token is [multilib] (one [<pkg>.<lib>/] subtree per library), [root]
(a single package at the version root) or [subdir] (a [<pkg>/] subtree per
package, e.g. js_of_ocaml, tyxml). See [(hosted …)] in
{{!page-"config"}Configuration} and {{!page-"commands"}[wodoc requalify-xrefs]}.

{1 A blog}

Drop dated [.mld] posts ([YYYY-MM-DD-slug.mld]) in a directory, add a [(blog …)]
stanza, and [wodoc build] lists them in the navigation, expands a "latest posts"
widget on the landing and can emit an Atom feed for syndication. The full recipe
is on its own page: {{!page-"blog"}Adding a blog}.

{1 Markdown and llms.txt for AI tools}

By default [wodoc build] also emits, next to every HTML page, a {b Markdown twin}
and a per-project [llms.txt] / [llms-full.txt] index (the
{{:https://llmstxt.org}llms.txt} convention), and adds a
[<link rel="alternate" type="text/markdown">] to each page. This keeps your docs
readable by plain-text tooling and LLMs at no extra effort. Turn it off with
[(markdown false)] in the config.

{1:deployment Versioning and deployment}

A build is one version directory; releases are frozen snapshots:

- {b CI builds [dev/]} on each push — [wodoc build --out _site/dev --label dev].
- {b A release freezes it}: {{!page-"commands"}[wodoc release]}
  [--site <gh-pages> --version 1.0.0] copies [dev/] to [1.0.0/], repoints the
  [latest] symlink and refreshes [versions.json]. Frozen pages are never rebuilt;
  the version [<select>] reads [versions.json] at load time, so even old pages
  list the current set.

Deploy the tree to GitHub Pages (or any static host). With a {b relative}
[(css …)] theme and a local [(highlight …)] (as in the starter), the site is
self-contained and deploys at {b any path} — a [you.github.io] site, a custom
domain, or a plain project page ([you.github.io/PROJECT/]) — as long as [(pub)]
matches the path it is served at (so the version selector switches correctly). If
you keep the {e absolute} stylesheet default instead, then [/css/] must be served
at the {b domain root} (a user/org site or a custom domain), since
[you.github.io/PROJECT/] would resolve [/css/…] outside your repo.

Worked CI examples:

- a generic gh-pages workflow:
  {{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/blob/master/examples/starter/deploy.yml}[examples/starter/deploy.yml]};
- wodoc's own (it dogfoods itself):
  {{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/blob/master/.github/workflows/doc.yml}[.github/workflows/doc.yml]}
  and {{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/blob/master/doc/README.md}[doc/README.md]}.

{1 A copy-paste starter}

Rather than assemble the menu, stylesheet and workflow by hand, start from
{{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/tree/master/examples/starter}[examples/starter]}:
copy [wodoc], [menu.html], [css/] and [deploy.yml] into your project, change the
names, and you have a themed, versioned, deployable site. Its
{{:https://github.com/ocsigen/wodoc/blob/master/examples/starter/README.md}README}
is the five-minute version of this page.
